               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290611-278-person2034">
                  MARK 
                  FULTON
               <interp inst="t18290611-278-person2034" type="surname" value="FULTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-278-person2034" type="given" value="MARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290611-278-person2034" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to Messrs. Pocock and Son, <rs id="t18290611-278-viclabel1459" type="occupation">coal-merchants</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-278-victim2033 t18290611-278-viclabel1459"></join>, of <placeName id="t18290611-278-crimeloc1460">St. Bride's-wharf, Whitefriars</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-278-crimeloc1460" type="placeName" value="St. Bride's-wharf, Whitefriars"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290611-278-crimeloc1460" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290611-278-off1457 t18290611-278-crimeloc1460"></join>. On the 9th of June, about twelve o'clock, I saw the prisoners taking coals out of the Joseph barge, which laid on the shore - they reached them out of the barge, and put them into a bag on the side; neither of them were in the barge; they must have pushed one another up to have reached them - there was about a bushel and a half in the two sacks: I have seen them there frequently before - the coals could not have tumbled overboard, for they had not been in the mud, and there was a vacancy in the barge where they were taken; I had seen the coals safe the night before - I saw them both take coals out of the barge; I saw Spencer taking them out of the barge - he reached them by standing on his toes; there were five in all - Spencer was the biggest; I apprehended them directly; I have warned them at least fifty times.</p>
               <p>JAMES YATES. I am a beadle. I was sent for, and found the prisoners by the side of the barge; they took up their bag, moved on the puddle-dock, and I secured them.</p>
               <p>SPENCER'S Defence. I came along the shore all the way from the Temple, and picked the coals up at several places.</p>
               <p>COSTON'S Defence. I say the same.</p>
               <p>SPENCER - <rs id="t18290611-278-verdict1461" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290611-278-verdict1461" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 18.</p>
